\textbf{Analysis of the Problem:}

The dataset contains \textbf{mixed variable types}:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{Quantitative (Continuous):} Monthly income (₹8,000–₹95,000)
\item \textit{Qualitative (Categorical):} Occupational status and housing type
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Correct Strategy — Option B}:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Income data} (continuous): Should be \textbf{grouped into class intervals} with appropriate width. Example: ₹10,000 range intervals balance detail and clarity for 1,200 observations.
\item \textbf{Qualitative variables} (occupational status, housing type): Should be presented as \textbf{separate categorical distributions} or \textbf{cross-tabulated (contingency tables)} to show relationships without forcing them into continuous groupings.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Why Other Options Fail}:

\textbf{Option A — FALSE:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Combining income with occupational categories creates unnecessarily complex tables.
\item Omitting housing type wastes information and violates data integrity principles.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Option C — FALSE:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Treating all 1,200 income values as individual categories produces an \textbf{unusable frequency distribution table} with 1,200+ rows.
\item Class intervals are \textit{essential} for continuous data summarization.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Option D — FALSE:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Income data exclusion eliminates primary information.
\item Quantitative analysis is fundamental to statistics; it does not require advanced methods at the classification stage.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Key Principle}: \textit{Classify quantitative variables using grouped frequency distributions with meaningful class intervals; present qualitative variables in separate categorical or cross-tabulated formats to preserve information structure.}

