\textbf{Analysis of this data classification quality control scenario:}

\textbf{Record Inventory:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Total received: 2,647 + 1,834 + 3,219 + 156 + 23 = 7,879
\item Valid classified: 7,700 records
\item Problematic: 156 (missing) + 23 (contradictory) = 179 records (2.27\%)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Evaluation of each option:}

\textbf{Option A \u2014 Incomplete approach:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Direct exclusion without attempting recovery is premature when source documents may contain clarifying information.
\item Missing region codes and contradictory codes may be resolvable through source verification (checking original survey forms, enumerator notes, or database cross-references).
\item While justifiable if verification is impossible, this option skips the recovery step that should precede exclusion in official statistical practice.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Option B \u2014 CORRECT:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Represents the \textbf{standard hierarchical protocol} for handling problematic records: attempt recovery first, exclude only if recovery fails.
\item \textbf{Source verification} can resolve many classification issues: illegible entries can sometimes be read with care, contradictions can be resolved by cross-referencing enumerator field notes or checking if the record belongs to a household straddling region boundaries.
\item Records successfully reclassified are retained, improving data completeness and reducing bias from arbitrary exclusion.
\item Records that cannot be resolved are excluded with documented methodology, maintaining statistical integrity.
\item This preserves data quality while maximizing the usable sample size—a core objective in official statistics.
\item Provides the most defensible audit trail for administrative and peer review.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Option C \u2014 Violates Statistical Principles:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Proportional allocation of 156 missing records assumes they follow the distribution of classified records without evidence. This introduces \textbf{artificial variability}.
\item Assigning the 23 contradictory records to the modal region (Rural: 3,219) is arbitrary and introduces \textbf{systematic bias}, artificially inflating one region's frequency.
\item Treating erroneous/unclassified data as valid without attempting recovery corrupts the classification table's integrity.
\item Absence of documentation violates transparency standards for official statistical production.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Option D \u2014 Data Preservation vs. Analytical Clarity:}
\begin{itemize}
\item While creating an 'Unclassified' category preserves all records and is transparent, it conflates two distinct quality issues: \textbf{missing data} (lost during collection) and \textbf{contradictory/erroneous data} (collected incorrectly).
\item A four-way classification table complicates analysis when the primary research objective is to understand region-consumption associations across the three planned regions, not to analyze classification failures.
\item Retaining 179 unresolved problematic records as a fourth category dilutes the analytical value of the contingency table and suggests inadequate data quality control.
\item This approach is appropriate for exploratory data analysis but inappropriate for finalizing an official classification table without prior recovery attempts.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Best Practice in Official Statistics:}
The SSC/JSO-level data management protocol prioritizes:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Recovery}: Attempt source verification to resolve ambiguities and correct errors.
\item \textbf{Exclusion with Documentation}: Only exclude records that cannot be resolved, with transparent reporting of exclusion rates and reasons.
\item \textbf{Integrity}: Never impute or allocate problematic records without justified methodology, and never retain unresolved erroneous data as valid analytical units.
\end{enumerate}

