\textbf{Step 4 — Calculate Coefficient of Variation:}

$$CV = \frac{s}{\bar{x}} \times 100\% = \frac{4.944}{37} \times 100\% \approx 13.36\%$$

\textbf{Key Concept:} The coefficient of variation is a dimensionless measure of relative variability, expressed as a percentage of the mean. It is particularly useful for comparing the consistency of datasets with different scales or units. A lower CV indicates greater consistency in production. For sample data, we use $n-1$ in the denominator (Bessel's correction).

