\textbf{Coefficient of Skewness (Moment-based):} The coefficient of skewness is defined as:

$$\gamma_1 = \frac{\mu_3}{\sigma^3}$$

where $\mu_3$ is the third central moment and $\sigma$ is the standard deviation.

\textbf{Step 1 — Find standard deviation:}
$$\sigma = \sqrt{\mu_2} = \sqrt{4} = 2$$

\textbf{Step 2 — Calculate $\sigma^3$:}
$$\sigma^3 = 2^3 = 8$$

\textbf{Step 3 — Apply the formula:}
$$\gamma_1 = \frac{0.5}{8} = 0.03125$$

\textbf{Interpretation:} The positive value indicates a \textbf{right-skewed (positively skewed)} distribution. The small magnitude (close to zero) indicates weak skewness, approaching symmetry.

