The \textbf{coefficient of kurtosis} ($\beta_2$), also known as Pearson's measure of kurtosis, is defined as:
$$\beta_2 = \frac{\mu_4}{\mu_2^2}$$

where $\mu_2$ is the \textbf{second central moment} (variance) and $\mu_4$ is the \textbf{fourth central moment}.

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{align}
\mu_2 &= 25 \text{ (variance)} \\
\mu_4 &= 1406.25 \text{ (fourth central moment)}
\end{align}

\textbf{Step 1:} Calculate $\mu_2^2$:
$$\mu_2^2 = (25)^2 = 625$$

\textbf{Step 2:} Apply the coefficient of kurtosis formula:
$$\beta_2 = \frac{\mu_4}{\mu_2^2} = \frac{1406.25}{625} = 2.25$$

\textbf{Interpretation:}
The \textbf{coefficient of kurtosis} ($\beta_2 = 2.25$) indicates the degree of peakedness of the distribution. Since $\beta_2 > 3$ would indicate a leptokurtic (peaked) distribution, $\beta_2 = 2.25$ indicates a \textbf{platykurtic} (flatter) distribution relative to the normal distribution.

\textbf{Key Point:} This is the standard definition used in SSC CGL Tier 2 Statistics. Do not confuse this with excess kurtosis, which is defined as $\gamma_2 = \beta_2 - 3 = 2.25 - 3 = -0.75$.

