The slope of the regression line of $Y$ on $X$ is given by the formula:

$$b_{YX} = r \cdot \frac{\sigma_Y}{\sigma_X}$$

where $r$ is the correlation coefficient, $\sigma_Y$ is the standard deviation of $Y$, and $\sigma_X$ is the standard deviation of $X$.

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{align}
r &= 0.8 \\
\sigma_X &= 6 \\
\sigma_Y &= 10
\end{align}

\textbf{Calculation:}
$$b_{YX} = 0.8 \times \frac{10}{6} = 0.8 \times \frac{5}{3} = \frac{4}{3} \approx 1.333$$

\textbf{Key Concept:} The regression coefficient depends on three components: the correlation strength ($r$), the variability in $Y$ (numerator), and the variability in $X$ (denominator). A correlation of 0.8 indicates a strong positive relationship, and the slope magnitude reflects how steeply $Y$ changes with $X$.

